When empress in her own right, she seems to have been enormously demanding, uprooting her villages, expelling their inhabitants and compounding their impoverishment.

I still remember reading an article by Joy Phumaphi, an epidemiologist from Botswana, comparing Botswana and Swaziland in the mid-1990s, referring to outsiders’ perception of King Sobhuza as “the Rastafarian King.” This laborious imagery worked, though it was completely off-the mark. Our association of the ridiculous and criminal with marijuana, hallucinogens and prostitution of young women, when in fact Rastafarianism carries a spiritual gravitas whose depth is unrivalled. It is true that the king smoked marijuana, as his subjects did, but that was not worthy of a news flash. More common was cannabis farming to supplement shot-term incomes.

The king taught me to respect a queen who triumphed anonymously. She was a tall, large-bosomed lady pursuing her own agenda with confidence, determination, and self-discipline. We were not married; we lived across the yard from one another; but our careers in Swaziland coincided over more than 15 years.
